===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|botany}} One of the [[small]] [[drupelike|drupe-like]] [[subdivision]]s which [[compose]] the [[outer]] [[layer#Noun|layer]] of certain [[fruit#Noun|fruit]] such as [[blackberry|blackberries]] or [[raspberry|raspberries]]. {{defdate|from mid 19th c.}}
#: {{synonyms|en|drupel}}
#: {{ux|en|It is best to pick the berries while all '''drupelets''' are of a consistent, dark red coloration.}}
#: {{ux|en|The passengers on the chock-full boat were packed across the deck like '''drupelets'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Asa Gray|authorlink=Asa Gray|chapter=How Plants are Propagated or Multiplied in Numbers|title=Botany for Young People and Common Schools. How Plants Grow, a Simple Introduction to Structural Botany.{{nb...|With a Popular Flora, or an Arrangement and Description of Common Plants, both Wild and Cultivated. Illustrated by 500 Wood Engravings.}}|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Ivison, Blakeman, Taylor, & Co.|year=1858|section=section IV (Fruit and Seed), §&nbsp;1 (Seed-vessels), paragraph 244|page=81|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=excFAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA81|oclc=505717616|passage=''Aggregated Fruits'' are close clusters of simple fruits all of the same flower. The raspberry and blackberry are good examples. In these, each grain is a '''''drupelet''''' or stone-fruit, like a cherry or peach on a very small scale.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=A[lbert] S[pear] Hitchcock|authorlink=A. S. Hitchcock|chapter=Fruits and Seeds|title=Field Work for the Local Botanist|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Published by the author{{nb...|1867 Park Road, Washington, D.C.}}; composed and printed at the Waverley Press, Inc.{{nb...|Baltimore, Md., U.S.A.}}|year=1931|page=22|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=VE4XAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA4-PP26|oclc=1131468420|passage=The fruits of the genus Rubus (blackberry, raspberry) are aggregates of small drupes ('''drupelets''') upon the receptacle of a single flower, each '''drupelet''' from a single pistil.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Bernadine C. Strik|chapter=Growth and Development|editors=Harvey K. Hall and Richard C. Funt|title=Blackberries and Their Hybrids|series=Crop Production Science in Horticulture|seriesvolume=26|location=Wallingford, Oxfordshire; Boston, Mass.|publisher=[[w:Centre for Agriculture and Bioscience International|CABI]]|year=2017|page=29|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=OY1FDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA29|isbn=978-1-78064-668-8|passage=Each fertilized pistil/ovule will develop into a fleshy '''drupelet''' containing one seed  (a pyrene). Erect and semi-erect blackberry cultivars produce fruit with relatively large pyrenes compared to those of trailing blackberries.}}

